<font color="#FF0000">A RESPONSE</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug  2  7:11:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz,<br><br>
There is such a thing as overstating a position. I am very much interested in fair dialogue and feel that my contributions have added a great deal to this pursuit. <br><br>
There comes a point where stating of positions reaches a full circle. I have arrived there. I, too, am getting &quot;tired&quot;. My ONLY purpose is to state my position - not to change someone elses.<br><br>
The way I feel about the war is well known. Not only here on this site, but also in the small town where I live. I have no doubt that my opinions clash with quite a few others. They are only opinions and don't necessarily indicate that I am unable to interact with others in the community. My life consists of many accomplishments. The greatest of which has been my ability to work together with people who were different from me politically. Can our leaders in Washington claim as much?<br><br>
When we summon up the courage to voice a viewpoint that is unpopular there is always the risk that what we say is going to be openly criticized. What we then learn about ourselves is whether or not we have the strength of our convictions! If one is absolutely, in the strongest possible sense, TRUE TO HIMSELF, then criticism doesn't matter.<br><br>
The namecalling and the baiting indicates a desire to chase those, with whom we disagree, away from the dialogue. It does NOT in any way, shape, or form, strengthen our point of view. If we are true to ourselves and confident in our viewpoints then why is it necessary to attempt to silence others? Intimidation should never be allowed to flourish.<br><br>
One more thing. Vietnam should never be allowed to define our entire lives. It represents about 2% of mine. The other 98% of my life is constituted of the aforementioned accomplishments, but also my life is testament to a great many failures and setbacks. We ALL need to remember this when we engage in insults and judgments.<br><br>
&quot;He who is without sin should cast the first stone.&quot;<br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


